1 Preamble

We will follow chapter Chapter 21: Creating packages for the code of the package npar. The package building procedure is substantially simplified using Package Projects and the Build tap in RStudio.

2 Installing the Package npar

Make sure that the Rtools are installed on your computer: https://cran.r-project.org/bin/windows/Rtools/installer.html. These tools allow you to build bundled or binary packages.

  • Bundles packages have the extension *.tar.gz and can be installed on any system. The Rtools are needed to install bundles.

    Important: If a library is installed from a bundle, dependent packages are not installed and must be manually downloaded. A dependent package is a library on which the package the current library depends to run properly.

  • Binary packages are specific for the operating system. For instance, for Windows R implementations they have the extension *.zip. These libraries automatically install dependent packages.

There is subtle difference in the terminology: A package is a collection of files making up the add-on, whereas a library is the physical installation of the package in Rs library system on the hard-drive.

> install.packages("F:\\Lectures2020\\EPPS6324\\CreatingPackage\\npar_1.0.tar.gz", repos=NULL)
R> Installing package into 'C:/Users/Michael/Documents/R/win-library/3.5'
R> (as 'lib' is unspecified)
> library(npar)

You will receive in Rs console the following installation log:

4 Tools to Build Libraries

Several external tools and library are needed to build packages with RStudio:

  • Rtools is needed for Windows computers. It is a stand-alone program. Mac and Linux computers may have different requirements. Click here for more information.

  • It may be required to install external \(\LaTeX\) editor programs. For Windows see MiTeX and for Mac see MacTeX.

The required libraries below are part of the standard installation of RStudio:

  • The library roxygen2 to build the data and function help files.

  • The library devtools with automates building a package.

  • See also the package development prerequisits

5 Functions and Data of npar

Each function has a header with standardized information tags for its help-file. Each documentation line is preceded by the characters #'. Functions in the library roxygen2 will use this information to generate the functions documentation.

The online help Help > Roxygen Quick Reference list the most commonly used keyword of function documentations.

5.1 The oneway Function

The function oneway is the working horse of the package. Its results are defined as S3 class class(results) <- c("oneway"). Furthermore, the function is parsing its input arguments. The parameter@exportmakes the function available and adds it to theNAMESPACE`.

#' @title Nonparametric group comparisons
#'
#' @description
#' \code{oneway} computes nonparametric group comparisons, including an
#' omnibus test and post-hoc pairwise group comparisons.
#'
#' @details
#' This function computes an omnibus Kruskal-Wallis test that the
#' groups are equal, followed by all pairwise comparisons using
#' Wilcoxon Rank Sum tests. Exact Wilcoxon tests can be requested if
#' there are no ties on the dependent variable. The p-values are 
#' adjusted for mulitple comparisons using the \code{\link{p.adjust}} 
#' function. 
#' 
#' @param formula an object of class formula, relating the dependent variable 
#' to the grouping variable.
#' @param data a data frame containing the variables in the model.
#' @param exact logical. If \code{TRUE}, calculate exact Wilcoxon tests.
#' @param sort logical. If \code{TRUE}, sort groups by median dependent variable values.
#' @param method method for correcting p-values for multiple comparisons.
#' @export
#' @return a list with 7 elements:
#' \item{CALL}{function call}
#' \item{data}{data frame containing the depending and grouping variable}
#' \item{sumstats}{data frame with descriptive statistics by group}
#' \item{kw}{results of the Kruskal-Wallis test}
#' \item{method}{method used to adjust p-values}
#' \item{wmc}{data frame containing the multiple comparisons}
#' \item{vnames}{variable names} 
#' @author Rob Kabacoff <rkabacoff@@statmethods.net>
#' @examples
#' results <- oneway(hlef ~ region, life)
#' summary(results)
#' plot(results, col="lightblue", main="Multiple Comparisons",
#'      xlab="US Region", ylab="Healthy Life Expectancy at Age 65")

oneway <- function(formula, data, exact=FALSE, sort=TRUE,               
                method=c("holm", "hochberg", "hommel", "bonferroni",      
                         "BH", "BY", "fdr", "none")){
  
  if (missing(formula) || class(formula) != "formula" ||
        length(all.vars(formula)) != 2)                                   
       stop("'formula' is missing or incorrect")

  method <- match.arg(method)

  df <- model.frame(formula, data)                            
  y <- df[[1]]
  g <- as.factor(df[[2]])
  vnames <- names(df)
  
  if(sort) g <- reorder(g, y, FUN=median)                           
  groups <- levels(g)
  k <- nlevels(g)
  
  getstats <- function(x)(c(N = length(x), Median = median(x),      
                          MAD = mad(x)))
  sumstats <- t(aggregate(y, by=list(g), FUN=getstats)[2])
  rownames(sumstats) <- c("n", "median", "mad")
  colnames(sumstats) <- groups
  
  kw <- kruskal.test(formula, data)                             
  wmc <- NULL
  for (i in 1:(k-1)){
    for (j in (i+1):k){
      y1 <- y[g==groups[i]]
      y2 <- y[g==groups[j]] 
      test <- wilcox.test(y1, y2, exact=exact)
      r <- data.frame(Group.1=groups[i], Group.2=groups[j], 
                      W=test$statistic[[1]], p=test$p.value)
      # note the [[]] to return a single number
      wmc <- rbind(wmc, r)
    }
  }
  wmc$p <- p.adjust(wmc$p, method=method)
  
  
  data <- data.frame(y, g)                                    
  names(data) <- vnames
  results <- list(CALL = match.call(), 
                  data=data,
                  sumstats=sumstats, kw=kw, 
                  method=method, wmc=wmc, vnames=vnames)
  class(results) <- c("oneway", "list")
  return(results)
}

For information on S3 class objects and their function system (a.k.a methods) please see Kabacoff Section 20.3: Object oriented programming.

5.2 The summary.oneway function

This function prints the results of the oneway function in an organized fashion onto the screen. It is tiddly linked to the object class oneway and only work for objects from this class.

The keyword @method summary oneway establishes the connection. It is shown in the NAMESPACE. The query inherits(object, "oneway") checks whether the input object is of the proper class.

#' @title Summarize oneway nonparametric analyses
#'
#' @description
#' \code{summary.oneway} summarizes the results of a oneway 
#' nonparametric analysis.
#'
#' @details
#' This function prints a summary of analyses produced by
#' the \code{\link{oneway}} function. This includes descriptive
#' statistics by group, an omnibus Kruskal-Wallis test, and 
#' Wilcoxon pairwise multiple comparisons.
#' 
#' @param object an object of class \code{oneway}.
#' @param ... additional parameters.
#' @method summary oneway
#' @export
#' @return the input object is returned silently.
#' @author Rob Kabacoff <rkabacoff@@statmethods.net>
#' @examples
#' results <- oneway(hlef ~ region, life)
#' summary(results)

summary.oneway <- function(object, ...){
  if (!inherits(object, "oneway")) 
    stop("Object must be of class 'oneway'")
    
  if(!exists("digits")) digits <- 4L
  
  kw <- object$kw
  wmc <- object$wmc
  
  cat("data:", object$vnames[1], "on", object$vnames[2], "\n\n")
  
  cat("Omnibus Test\n")                        
  cat(paste("Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = ", 
             round(kw$statistic,4), 
            ", df = ", round(kw$parameter, 3), 
            ", p-value = ", 
               format.pval(kw$p.value, digits = digits), 
            "\n\n", sep=""))
  
  cat("Descriptive Statistics\n")     
  print(object$sumstats, ...)
  
  
  wmc$stars <- " "                  
  wmc$stars[wmc$p <   .1] <- "."
  wmc$stars[wmc$p <  .05] <- "*"
  wmc$stars[wmc$p <  .01] <- "**"
  wmc$stars[wmc$p < .001] <- "***"
  names(wmc)[which(names(wmc)=="stars")] <- " "                          
  
  cat("\nMultiple Comparisons (Wilcoxon Rank Sum Tests)\n")    
  cat(paste("Probability Adjustment = ", object$method, "\n", sep=""))
  print(wmc, ...)
  cat("---\nSignif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1\n")
}

5.3 The data life.rda and its help file life.r

Data-sets, which reside in the sub-directory .\\data, have no provision to include a their documentation directly into them. Therefore, a helper function with the same root name is required. The syntax of the data-set documentations varies slightly.

#' @title Healthy Life Expectancy at Age 65
#' 
#' @description A dataset containing the healthy life expectancy (expected
#' years of life in good health) at age 65, by US state in 2007-2009. 
#' Estimates are reported separately for men and women.

#' @docType data

#' @name life
#' @usage life
#' @format A data frame with 50 rows and 4 variables. The variables
#' are as follows:

6 Building a Package with RStudio

A full documentation on building packages in RStudio can be found online at in the first few chapters of Wickhams R Packages book. The last few chapters cover more specialized topics. For our purposes, however, this tutorial and Kabacoffs Chapter 21: Creating a package is sufficient.

Compared to Kabacoffs instructions, using RStudio makes building a package more streamlined.

From here on, a second instance of RStudio will be open that allows us to re-build the package npar with the new name myNpar.

A cheatsheet can be downloaded from RStudios server.

6.1 Start a New Project

Start a new project with File > New Project > New Directory > Package with devtools and then select the the name of your package. Here myNpar has been selected.

These steps generate a new sub-directory, which has the content:

6.2 Populating the Package with Data and Functions

  • Inside the package directory generate a new sub-directory labelled data.

  • Copy the data-set life.rda into the data sub-directory.

  • Copy the functions npar.r, oneway.r, plot.r, print.r, summary.r and life.r into the R sub-directory.

6.3 Editing the DESCRIPTION and code

  • In Rs file browser click on the DESCRIPTION file and change its content to: Then save the file.

  • To edit a the code or documentation of a function open the function in the script editor by using Rs file browser. Once you are done save your edits.

6.4 Building the Online Help

In the Build menu select the option Document.

Functions in the library roxygen2 build the online help documentation in the sub-directory man and populate the NAMESPACE with the necessary information of the exported functions.

Warning: You almost never need to edit the file NAMESPACE.

6.5 Building the Package Bundle

To build the package bundle and install the updated package directly into your pool of libraries use the menu Build > Clean and Rebuild:

The build information should not have error messages. You can get immediately to your rebuild library in the online help. By default the new package is loaded into your R session.

To build a package bundle for distribution use the Console commands

> devtools::build()

This is the only option to also process vignettes of your package. vignettes are lengthy R markdown documents that demonstrate to your clients what your package can do.

Your new bundle file myNpar_0.1.1.tar.gz is saved into the directory above your package projects directory. It can be installed with on other computers with

> install.packages("Drive:/Path/myNpar_0.1.1.tar.gz", repos=NULL)
